
- Evaluate the integral 

  :: _sequence_ ::

  "Evaluate \( I(\nu) = \int_0^\infty \; \nu^\frac{1}{2}\, e^{-\nu}\; d\nu \)" (note) "\(I(\nu)\) is not to be understood as a function of \(\nu\)"

    " (note) The integrand is fully analytic so we are free to move the limit and differentiate under the integral sign etc.
  
  "Let \( \nu = \lim_{a\rightarrow 0} \left\lbrack \left( \nu^\frac{1}{2} + \frac{a}{2} \right)^2 - \frac{a^2}{4} \right\rbrack \)"

  "Then \( I(\nu) = \lim_{a\rightarrow 0} \int_0^\infty  \nu^\frac{1}{2} \exp\left(- \left( \nu^\frac{1}{2} + \frac{a}{2} \right)^2 - \frac{a^2}{4} \right) d\nu  \)"

  "\( I(\nu) = \lim_{a\rightarrow 0} -\frac{d}{da} \;  \int_0^\infty  \exp\left(- \left( \nu^\frac{1}{2} + \frac{a}{2} \right)^2 - \frac{a^2}{4} \right) d\nu   \)"
  
  "Let \( u = (\nu^\frac{1}{2} + \frac{a}{2}), du = \frac{1}{2}\nu^{-\frac{1}{2}} d\nu \)" (note) "i.e. \( (u - \frac{a}{2})= \nu^\frac{1}{2},   d\nu = 2(u - \frac{a}{2})du \)"

  "Now: \( I(u) = \lim_{a\rightarrow} -\frac{d}{da} \;  \int_0^\infty du\; \left(u - \frac{a}{2}\right) e^{-u^2+a^2/4} \)"

  "We know by polar coordinates that: \( \int_0^\infty \; e^{-r^2} dr  = \sqrt{\pi}/2 \)"

  "Integrating by parts: \( \int_0^\infty u e^{-u^2}\,du = -\frac{1}{2} \lbrack e^{-u^2}\rbrack_0^\infty = \frac{1}{2} \)"

  "Thus: \( I(u) = \lim_{a\rightarrow} -2\frac{d}{da} \;\left\lbrack (\frac{1}{2}-\frac{a}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{\pi}) e^{a^2/4} \right\rbrack    \)"

  "\( I(u) =-2  \lim_{a\rightarrow}  \;\left\lbrack \frac{2a}{4} (\frac{1}{2}-\ldots) - \frac{1}{4}\sqrt{\pi}   \right\rbrack\;e^{a^2/4} \)"

  "Finally, taking the limit, \(I \rightarrow  \frac{\sqrt \pi}{2}\)"

